Posted: Wed Sep 18, 2013 9:11 am
Yes folks, I'm here today to tell you about a web-based game, Cookie Clicker (or Cookie Clicker 2, if you ran into the developer's first prototype now named "Cookie Clicker Classic.")http://orteil.dashnet.org/cookieclicker/When you start the game, you're presented with a cookie icon. Click it and you receive one cookie. So far so good, right? Nope. You're never getting into the cookie production big leagues one at a time, son! The game has upgrades, structures that you buy (with cookies) to automate production, and a system of multipliers and bonuses. It can just run passively in the background once you have automation set up (great for overnight or work or whatever) but there's a way to "play" it as well, beyond just clicking cookies.This *is* a game about optimizing outcomes and has surprising depth beyond just "playing a spreadsheet." There's definitely that strategy aspect to it in terms of figuring out how to optimize your build, and how to continually optimize it as you go into and out of different phases of the game.It's still under active development and the last update added in the final "core game" structure as well as a number of tweaks. Dungeons are on track for the next update late this month or next month. What one does in a cookie dungeon is a mystery to me.The game has a full Wiki, which I won't link but you can easily find it as it's full of spoilers. I'd try to get through at least a few days before checking out what you're missing. Also, it would be better to avoid the change log as it contains spoilers.If you're having trouble understanding optimizations as you go along and can't find the efficient way to do things, there is an advanced mode:
Spoiler: show
It's called Cookie Monster mode and is activated by passing the game a snippet of Javascript (below) by means of a bookmark. Just put the following snippet into your bookmarks with the "address" being the code:Code:javascript: (function () {var jA = document.createElement('script');jA.setAttribute('type', 'text/javascript');jA.setAttribute('src', 'http://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.10.2/jquery.min.js');jA.onload = function() { var jB = document.createElement('script'); jB.setAttribute('type', 'text/javascript'); jB.setAttribute('src', 'http://pastebin.com/raw.php?i=2KRNm8Gm'); document.body.appendChild(jB);};document.body.appendChild(jA);}());This shows you precisely how much each structure is worth, as the values vary based on multipliers, and shows you the payout in terms of maximum efficiency. It also cleans up some of the interface (abbreviating millions, billions, trillions, quadrillions, etc.), color codes for efficiency and shows timers for certain events and other behind-the-scenes data.It's not cheating, but again, I'd recommend playing for a day or two before going into "advanced" mode. Once you've gone pretty far in the game, it does become VERY helpful, though.
So get to clicking!
